---
import PageShell from '../../../../components/PageShell.astro';
import ComparisonTable from '../../../../components/ComparisonTable.astro';

const tocItems = [
  { id: 'overview', text: 'Overview', level: 2 },
  { id: 'healthcare-system', text: 'Healthcare System', level: 2 },
  { id: 'visa-requirements', text: 'Visa Options', level: 2 },
  { id: 'insurance-requirements', text: 'Insurance Requirements', level: 2 },
  { id: 'recommended-providers', text: 'Recommended Providers', level: 2 },
  { id: 'costs', text: 'Expected Costs', level: 2 },
  { id: 'scenarios', text: 'Real-World Scenarios', level: 2 },
  { id: 'faqs', text: 'Common Questions', level: 2 },
];

const relatedLinks = [
  { title: 'Canada Insurance Guide', href: '/countries/canada/insurance' },
  { title: 'Insurance for Seniors', href: '/insurance-for/seniors' },
  { title: 'USA for Seniors', href: '/insurance-for/seniors/in/usa' },
  { title: 'UK for Seniors', href: '/insurance-for/seniors/in/uk' },
  { title: 'Australia for Seniors', href: '/insurance-for/seniors/in/australia' },
];

const providerColumns = [
  { key: 'provider', header: 'Provider' },
  { key: 'entryAge', header: 'Max Entry Age' },
  { key: 'renewal', header: 'Renewal' },
  { key: 'monthlyFrom', header: 'From (65-69)' },
  { key: 'canadaFit', header: 'Canada Fit' },
];

const providerRows = [
  { provider: 'Cigna Global', entryAge: '74', renewal: 'Lifetime', monthlyFrom: 'CAD 580-820/mo', canadaFit: 'Excellent' },
  { provider: 'BUPA Global', entryAge: '79', renewal: 'Lifetime', monthlyFrom: 'CAD 650-920/mo', canadaFit: 'Excellent' },
  { provider: 'Allianz Care', entryAge: '74', renewal: 'Lifetime', monthlyFrom: 'CAD 520-740/mo', canadaFit: 'Very Good' },
  { provider: 'GeoBlue', entryAge: '74', renewal: 'To 84', monthlyFrom: 'CAD 480-680/mo', canadaFit: 'Good' },
  { provider: 'Provincial Health (PR)', entryAge: 'No limit', renewal: 'N/A', monthlyFrom: 'Free-CAD 150', canadaFit: 'For PRs Only' },
];

const costColumns = [
  { key: 'category', header: 'Expense' },
  { key: 'monthly', header: 'Monthly' },
  { key: 'annual', header: 'Annual' },
];

const costRows = [
  { category: 'International Insurance (65-69)', monthly: 'CAD 520-820', annual: 'CAD 6,240-9,840' },
  { category: 'International Insurance (70-74)', monthly: 'CAD 720-1,050', annual: 'CAD 8,640-12,600' },
  { category: 'International Insurance (75-79)', monthly: 'CAD 950-1,400', annual: 'CAD 11,400-16,800' },
  { category: 'Provincial Health (BC/ON)', monthly: 'Free-CAD 150', annual: 'Tax-funded' },
  { category: 'Canadian Supplementary', monthly: 'CAD 150-400', annual: 'CAD 1,800-4,800' },
];
---

<PageShell
  title="Health Insurance for Seniors in Canada 2026 | Retirement Guide"
  description="Guide to health insurance for seniors retiring in Canada. Provincial healthcare, Super Visa, Toronto and Vancouver hospitals, and coverage for expats 65+."
  headline="Health Insurance for Seniors in Canada"
  subheadline="Canada offers universal healthcare for residents, English/French culture, and stunning natural beauty—but immigration for retirees requires family sponsorship or significant investment."
  heroImage="/images/countries/canada-hero-bg.png"
  tocItems={tocItems}
  relatedLinks={relatedLinks}
  ctaButtonText="Compare Senior Plans →"
  ctaButtonHref="/go/cigna-global"
>
  <h2 id="overview">Why Seniors Choose Canada</h2>
  <p>
    Canada offers exceptional quality of life, universal healthcare for residents, multicultural cities, and vast natural beauty. For seniors with Canadian family or those who qualify for permanent residence, it provides a safe, stable environment with familiar North American culture.
  </p>

  <p>
    Vancouver offers mild winters and Pacific Rim diversity. Toronto is Canada's largest city with excellent hospitals. Victoria on Vancouver Island has the mildest climate. Montreal provides European flair in French Canada. Calgary and Edmonton offer lower costs and proximity to the Rockies.
  </p>

  <div class="bg-primary-50 border border-primary-200 rounded-lg p-6 my-6">
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-primary-900 mb-3">Key Facts for Seniors</h3>
    <ul class="text-primary-800 space-y-2">
      <li><strong>Healthcare:</strong> Universal for residents; ranked highly globally</li>
      <li><strong>Languages:</strong> English and French (varies by province)</li>
      <li><strong>Cost of Living:</strong> CAD 3,000-5,000/month; Vancouver/Toronto highest</li>
      <li><strong>Climate:</strong> Cold winters (except BC coast); warm summers</li>
      <li><strong>Safety:</strong> Very safe; low crime rates</li>
      <li><strong>Immigration:</strong> Challenging for seniors without family ties</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <h2 id="healthcare-system">Canada's Healthcare System</h2>
  <p>
    Canada's Medicare system provides universal coverage for medically necessary hospital and physician services to citizens and permanent residents. Each province administers its own plan (OHIP in Ontario, MSP in BC, etc.). Coverage is comprehensive for hospital care but doesn't include prescriptions, dental, or vision.
  </p>

  <p>
    Healthcare quality is good, but wait times for specialists and elective procedures can be long—sometimes months. Many Canadians add private insurance for prescriptions, dental, vision, and semi-private hospital rooms. Major cities have excellent hospitals and specialists.
  </p>

  <div class="bg-amber-50 border border-amber-200 rounded-lg p-4 my-6">
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-amber-900 mb-2">Wait Times Reality</h3>
    <p class="text-amber-800 mb-0">
      Canadian healthcare wait times are significant. Median wait from GP referral to treatment is 27+ weeks for some procedures. Emergency care is immediate, but non-urgent specialist appointments and surgeries often require patience. Some Canadians travel to the US for faster care.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h2 id="visa-requirements">Visa Options for Seniors</h2>
  <p>
    Canada's immigration system is challenging for seniors without connections:
  </p>

  <h3>Super Visa (Parents/Grandparents)</h3>
  <p>
    For parents and grandparents of Canadian citizens/PRs. Allows stays up to 5 years at a time. Requires Canadian medical insurance of CAD 100,000+ minimum. Doesn't grant PR or provincial healthcare access.
  </p>

  <h3>Parent and Grandparent Sponsorship</h3>
  <p>
    Your Canadian citizen/PR child can sponsor you for permanent residence. Limited places, lottery system, and processing takes years. Once PR granted, access provincial healthcare after waiting period (typically 3 months).
  </p>

  <h3>Start-Up Visa</h3>
  <p>
    For entrepreneurs with innovative businesses. No age limit but requires active business involvement, not suitable for pure retirees.
  </p>

  <h3>Visitor Status</h3>
  <p>
    6-month visitor stays with possible extensions. No healthcare access—comprehensive travel insurance essential. Some retirees alternate between Canada and elsewhere ("snowbirds").
  </p>

  <h2 id="insurance-requirements">Insurance Requirements</h2>
  <p>
    Insurance requirements depend heavily on your status:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Super Visa:</strong> Minimum CAD 100,000 Canadian medical insurance required</li>
    <li><strong>Visitors:</strong> Comprehensive travel insurance essential (no public coverage)</li>
    <li><strong>New PRs:</strong> Private coverage during 3-month provincial waiting period</li>
    <li><strong>Established PRs:</strong> Provincial coverage; many add supplementary insurance</li>
  </ul>

  <div class="bg-blue-50 border border-blue-200 rounded-lg p-4 my-6">
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-blue-900 mb-2">Insurance Strategy for Canada</h3>
    <p class="text-blue-800 mb-0">
      Super Visa holders need Canadian medical insurance (minimum CAD 100,000) from approved providers. Long-term visitors need comprehensive international coverage. PRs get provincial coverage but should add private insurance for prescriptions, dental, and travel outside Canada.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h2 id="recommended-providers">Recommended Insurance Providers</h2>
  <p>
    For seniors in Canada, provider choice depends on your immigration status:
  </p>

  <ComparisonTable columns={providerColumns} rows={providerRows} />

  <h3>Why These Providers Work for Canada</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Cigna Global:</strong> Strong North American network, good for Super Visa compliance</li>
    <li><strong>BUPA Global:</strong> Highest entry age (79), comprehensive coverage</li>
    <li><strong>Allianz Care:</strong> Good value, Canadian network</li>
    <li><strong>GeoBlue:</strong> US-based with good Canada coverage; familiar to Americans</li>
  </ul>

  <div class="bg-primary-50 border border-primary-200 rounded-lg p-6 my-8">
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Get Personalized Senior Quotes</h3>
    <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-4">Compare coverage and pricing from providers that accept seniors for Canada.</p>
    <div class="flex flex-wrap gap-3">
      <a href="/go/cigna-global" class="inline-block px-5 py-2.5 bg-primary-600 text-white rounded-lg hover:bg-primary-700 transition-colors font-medium" style="color: white !important;">Get Cigna Quote</a>
      <a href="/go/bupa-global" class="inline-block px-5 py-2.5 bg-neutral-700 text-white rounded-lg hover:bg-neutral-800 transition-colors font-medium" style="color: white !important;">Get BUPA Quote</a>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2 id="costs">Expected Insurance Costs</h2>
  <p>
    Insurance costs in Canada are high due to North American healthcare pricing:
  </p>

  <ComparisonTable columns={costColumns} rows={costRows} />

  <h3>Cost-Saving Strategies</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Get PR:</strong> Provincial coverage is the most cost-effective option</li>
    <li><strong>Higher deductibles:</strong> CAD 5,000+ deductible reduces premiums significantly</li>
    <li><strong>US exclusion:</strong> If you won't visit the US, excluding it saves substantially</li>
    <li><strong>Snowbird pattern:</strong> Split time between Canada and a lower-cost country</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="scenarios">Real-World Scenarios</h2>

  <div class="space-y-6 my-8">
    <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Scenario 1: American Parent, 68</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-2"><strong>Situation:</strong> Daughter is Canadian citizen in Vancouver. Applying for Super Visa.</p>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-2"><strong>Solution:</strong> Cigna Global meeting CAD 100,000+ requirement. Can stay 5 years per visit.</p>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-0"><strong>Cost:</strong> ~CAD 700/month. No provincial healthcare access; must maintain insurance entire stay.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Scenario 2: British New PR, 72</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-2"><strong>Situation:</strong> Just received PR through family sponsorship. Moving to Toronto. 3-month OHIP waiting period.</p>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-2"><strong>Solution:</strong> BUPA Global for 3-month gap. Once OHIP active, add Canadian supplementary for prescriptions/dental.</p>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-0"><strong>Cost:</strong> BUPA ~CAD 800/month for 3 months. After: supplementary ~CAD 250/month.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Scenario 3: Snowbird Couple, Both 70</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-2"><strong>Situation:</strong> Splitting time: 6 months Canada (visitor), 6 months Portugal. No Canadian PR.</p>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-2"><strong>Solution:</strong> Allianz Care worldwide coverage including Canada. Portugal provides Schengen access.</p>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-0"><strong>Cost:</strong> ~CAD 1,200/month combined. Single policy covers both countries.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2 id="faqs">Common Questions</h2>

  <div class="space-y-6 my-8">
    <div class="border-b border-neutral-200 pb-4">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I retire to Canada without family there?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-0">
        Very difficult. Canada doesn't have a retirement visa. Without Canadian citizen/PR family to sponsor you, options are limited to business immigration (Start-Up Visa requires active business) or visitor status (6 months maximum). The Super Visa is only for parents/grandparents of citizens/PRs.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="border-b border-neutral-200 pb-4">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">How long is the family sponsorship wait?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-0">
        The Parents and Grandparents Program uses a lottery system with limited annual places (~10,000-20,000). If selected, processing takes 20-24 months. Many applicants aren't selected for years. The Super Visa is an alternative for those who want to be in Canada sooner.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="border-b border-neutral-200 pb-4">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What's the Super Visa insurance requirement?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-0">
        Super Visa requires Canadian medical insurance with minimum CAD 100,000 coverage, valid for at least 1 year, covering healthcare, hospitalization, and repatriation. Must be from a Canadian insurance company or international insurer with Canadian operations. You must maintain coverage your entire stay.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="border-b border-neutral-200 pb-4">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Are Canadian winters really that bad?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-0">
        It depends on location. Vancouver and Victoria have mild, rainy winters (rarely below 0°C). Toronto winters are cold (-5 to -15°C) with snow. Prairie cities (Calgary, Winnipeg) have harsh winters (-20 to -30°C). Many Canadian seniors become "snowbirds," spending winters in warmer climates.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="bg-primary-50 border border-primary-200 rounded-lg p-6 my-8">
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Ready to Compare Options?</h3>
    <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-4">Get quotes from providers that specialize in senior expat coverage for Canada.</p>
    <div class="flex flex-wrap gap-3">
      <a href="/go/cigna-global" class="inline-block px-5 py-2.5 bg-primary-600 text-white rounded-lg hover:bg-primary-700 transition-colors font-medium" style="color: white !important;">Get Cigna Quote</a>
      <a href="/go/allianz-care" class="inline-block px-5 py-2.5 bg-neutral-700 text-white rounded-lg hover:bg-neutral-800 transition-colors font-medium" style="color: white !important;">Get Allianz Quote</a>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6 mt-8">
    <p class="text-sm text-neutral-600 mb-0">
      <strong>Disclaimer:</strong> This guide is for informational purposes only. Insurance requirements, visa regulations, and healthcare access rules change regularly. Always verify current requirements with Canadian immigration and consult with a licensed insurance professional.
    </p>
  </div>
</PageShell>
